bibdata.title: Seeding figgy cache in development seems to block indexing to Solr

comments.body:
In order to index locally records with arks you should export in your local the env `FIGGY_ARK_CACHE_PATH`, Similar to how tests are running. 

If the env `FIGGY_ARK_CACHE_PATH` does not exist locally, traject.config is looking the /tmp/figgy_ark_cache  but because the file `tmp/figgy_ark_cache` is probably out of date or never created it takes a long time to run the solr seeding. 
```
1.export FIGGY_ARK_CACHE_PATH=spec/fixtures/marc_to_solr/figgy_ark_cache
2. bundle exec traject -c marc_to_solr/lib/traject_config.rb pathToFile -u http://localhost:solr-port/solr/marc-liberation-core-development
3. curl ‘http://localhost:solr-port/solr/marc-liberation-core-development/update?commit=true’
We should include the above in the documentation.

comments.body: Bucket created, and access details shared securely with the vendor this morning.

Attempting to upload the files to the S3 Bucket using only a browser yields the following for any `princeton.edu` hosts:

![image.png](https://images.zenhubusercontent.com/5b5b6aed981c3204c9ed06c8/d5ad3686-0bd7-457a-a170-0175bac7e8cf)

Attempting to install the PowerShell tools using the AWS documentation https://docs.aws.amazon.com/powershell/latest/userguide/pstools-s3-upload-object.html yields the following:

![image.png](https://images.zenhubusercontent.com/5b5b6aed981c3204c9ed06c8/02735914-4603-4e87-aeb1-3b1895752112)

Following the documentation for the `AWSCLI` utilities for Windows, the binary:

I am going to attempt to resolve this with a firewall update request on SN@P.
